Intro
While the housing crisis is present nearly everywhere across America,
how it manifests is unique to each and every place. Tackling the crisis
requires understanding a place’s existing market, the needs of its
residents, and the laws that shape how the market functions. This post
will examine Census data to learn: how many people live in the Memphis
area, how many housing units exist, how many are vacant, and how these
figures have changed over the past decade.
Population and Households
There are two main ways to measure population using Census data: the
total population and the number of households. The Census Bureau
publishes more robust data on households, so this figure is more
commonly used for in-depth housing analysis. Typically an increase (or
decrease) in the population is tandem with an increase (or decrease) in
the number of households. This was not the case in Memphis, where a
stagnant population illuminated changes in household composition.
The following table shows the total population, number of households,
and average household size in Memphis, Shelby County, and the Memphis
Metro Area. Below each area are the 2020 estimates and the percent
change from 2010 to 2020.


