While Memphis has a high vacancy rate (14.6%), the county outside the
city has a significantly lower rate of 5.2%. The county saw an increase
of 6,903 occupied units and a decrease in 761 vacant units, meaning at
least 6,142 new units were developed.
Removing the county’s data from the metro reveals that the outlying
area saw an increase in the number of vacant units and vacancy rate, in
contrast to the city and county. Overall, there was an increase of
12,992 occupied units AND an increase in 1,696 vacant units. This
combination of increased occupancy and vacancy signifies substantial new
development in areas outside Shelby County–at least 14,688 units. The
increase in the vacancy rate also suggest that supply in these areas may
exceed demand.
In total, at least 24,411 new housing units were developed in the
Memphis area from 2010-2020, with development primarily in the metro
area outside Shelby County.
Despite most development occurring outside the city limits and large
drops in vacancy, this data suggests Memphis still has tens of thousands
of existing units that should be available. However, the quality of
these homes may make them uninhabitable, the area may be undesirable, or
the costs may be too high for existing residents to afford. This
information is outside the scope of this post and further research is
needed to draw any conclusions.
Conclusion
Memphis’s population stagnated between 2010 and 2020, hovering around
635,000 people. Over this same time period, a decrease in average
household size lead to an increase in the number of households. This
means that while the population in the city remained flat, there was
still an increase in the demand for housing over the past decade.
Meanwhile, areas outside the city saw strong population/household
growth. Despite a recent desire by city officials to increase density,
new development over the past decade was primarily in the metro region
outside the county limits. Though the vacancy rate in Memphis has
decreased, the figure is still high and a large portion of the existing
housing stock should still be available for occupancy. Further research
is needed on the quality, cost, and location of this housing to
determine actual availability.
